WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.440
Tanya Filz, The resilient R champion, RStudio

00:00:09.440 --> 00:00:10.440
So my name is Tanya.

00:00:10.440 --> 00:00:13.040
I've been with RStudio for about two years now.

00:00:13.040 --> 00:00:18.620
So I work in customer success, so I work with several of our enterprise customers.

00:00:18.620 --> 00:00:22.920
My background is as a therapist, so that was my first career.

00:00:22.920 --> 00:00:28.280
And so I started to see these principles of resiliency in some of my strongest R champions.

00:00:28.280 --> 00:00:33.840
So I wanted to take some time to talk through what an R champion is, how you can improve

00:00:33.840 --> 00:00:35.880
your R championing.

00:00:35.880 --> 00:00:36.880
Is that a word?

00:00:36.880 --> 00:00:37.880
I think it is.

00:00:37.880 --> 00:00:38.880
Yeah.

00:00:38.880 --> 00:00:42.759
R championing and some of the barriers and some of the ways that I've seen folks be successful

00:00:42.759 --> 00:00:45.639
in overcoming those barriers.

00:00:45.639 --> 00:00:47.160
So who is an R champion?

00:00:47.160 --> 00:00:51.720
Well, probably a lot of you here are R champions.

00:00:51.720 --> 00:00:56.000
But these are some ideas that I came up with as I was thinking about what an R champion

00:00:56.000 --> 00:00:57.000
is.

00:00:57.720 --> 00:01:02.160
So an R champion is someone who uses R to accomplish the core goals and objectives of

00:01:02.160 --> 00:01:07.959
their job, promotes the use of R within their group and broader ecosystem that they live

00:01:07.959 --> 00:01:09.760
in.

00:01:09.760 --> 00:01:16.320
They contribute to the R community through RStudio community and Stack Overflow and other

00:01:16.320 --> 00:01:23.199
mediums, advocates for and takes ownership of R tooling in their environment.

00:01:23.199 --> 00:01:28.839
So one of the things that I'll talk a little bit more about later on is that sometimes

00:01:28.839 --> 00:01:33.720
what I see is that R is installed and left to IT to manage.

00:01:33.720 --> 00:01:37.400
And the teams that I see be the most successful are when a data scientist is really driving

00:01:37.400 --> 00:01:41.080
their R tool chain forward.

00:01:41.080 --> 00:01:45.919
And then an R champion is also someone who stays up to date on all things R and freely

00:01:45.919 --> 00:01:47.860
disseminates this information.

00:01:47.860 --> 00:01:52.320
So within their group at work, but also through other mediums.

00:01:52.320 --> 00:01:59.160
So through community, through R meetups and other channels.

00:01:59.160 --> 00:02:06.860
So I wanted to add in this slide for simple ideas to improve your R champion cred.

00:02:06.860 --> 00:02:12.380
So one easy one is to organize a lunch and learn for just R analysts or maybe analysts

00:02:12.380 --> 00:02:15.860
interested in R in your group.

00:02:15.860 --> 00:02:19.839
And then once you get this off the ground with your friends, invite more friends from

00:02:19.839 --> 00:02:21.179
parallel groups.

00:02:21.179 --> 00:02:23.220
So how do you get a hold of them?

00:02:23.220 --> 00:02:24.779
Start an internal Slack channel.

00:02:24.779 --> 00:02:30.940
So for folks in your broader organization that are using R. So I saw this be really

00:02:30.940 --> 00:02:36.559
successful in one of my accounts where there were several different branches that were

00:02:36.559 --> 00:02:40.539
all technically different orgs but under one broader org.

00:02:40.539 --> 00:02:44.699
And they started a Slack channel for all the different branches even though they were technically

00:02:44.699 --> 00:02:47.300
different companies under the same parent company.

00:02:47.300 --> 00:02:51.779
And it was really successful because when someone ran into a problem with their R code,

00:02:51.779 --> 00:02:59.020
they could rely on their broader colleagues in their bigger ecosystem for help.

00:02:59.020 --> 00:03:04.179
Be intentional about connecting with other R users at R meetups and R conferences and

00:03:04.179 --> 00:03:07.300
talk about the barriers that you're running into.

00:03:07.300 --> 00:03:09.220
Because chances are you're not alone.

00:03:09.220 --> 00:03:14.580
When you run into a barrier or someone says no to something that you want to do, chances

00:03:14.619 --> 00:03:18.419
are it can feel very isolated, but chances are you're not alone.

00:03:18.419 --> 00:03:20.100
Someone else has run into that.

00:03:20.100 --> 00:03:24.899
So talk about, you know, the 50,000-foot view of how things are going in your organizations

00:03:24.899 --> 00:03:28.020
with other R users.

00:03:28.020 --> 00:03:29.020
So what are some of the barriers?

00:03:29.020 --> 00:03:33.880
Now that I got you all stoked about being an R champion, what are some of the barriers

00:03:33.880 --> 00:03:35.660
that you might run into?

00:03:35.660 --> 00:03:40.539
So these are definitely not all of the barriers, but this is a short talk, so I can't go through

00:03:40.539 --> 00:03:42.380
all of them.

00:03:42.380 --> 00:03:45.740
So these are just a few of the ones that I came up with.

00:03:45.740 --> 00:03:49.059
So some of the ones that I see are the open source mentality.

00:03:49.059 --> 00:03:50.940
So that was kind of twofold.

00:03:50.940 --> 00:03:57.740
Why should we trust open source tools and why should we pay for open source tools?

00:03:57.740 --> 00:04:02.320
Funding issues, there's not enough money, IT support, and then, of course, internal

00:04:02.320 --> 00:04:06.059
political pressure, everyone's favorite.

00:04:06.059 --> 00:04:11.179
So why trust open source R?

00:04:11.179 --> 00:04:18.980
So one of the things that I've learned a lot about in my role is the different mentality.

00:04:18.980 --> 00:04:26.339
So the old school thought before open source became utilized in enterprise settings was

00:04:26.339 --> 00:04:31.540
that you buy your software from a big company that wrote the software, and then you have

00:04:31.540 --> 00:04:35.739
to pay for support to support that software.

00:04:35.739 --> 00:04:40.660
And I don't know if you've ever bought a software from a big company and then had it

00:04:40.660 --> 00:04:44.619
not function as you anticipated.

00:04:44.619 --> 00:04:48.260
And it's hard to really validate that because it's closed source, right?

00:04:48.260 --> 00:04:49.779
You cannot see the source code.

00:04:49.779 --> 00:04:56.859
You can't validate for yourself that the software will perform as anticipated.

00:04:56.859 --> 00:05:00.700
So active software utilization is more the open source mentality.

00:05:00.700 --> 00:05:07.339
The code is all there, and you have to or you can go in, look at the software, look

00:05:07.339 --> 00:05:13.779
at the code, and make sure it will do what you need it to do.

00:05:13.779 --> 00:05:18.299
And I will say it's a little bit higher investment with the active software utilization.

00:05:18.299 --> 00:05:23.660
So that's sometimes where you get some resistance is the fact that you're taking ownership of

00:05:23.660 --> 00:05:27.859
it and you're validating it yourself.

00:05:27.859 --> 00:05:32.260
So the nice thing about that, though, is open source technology, it's really hard to

00:05:32.260 --> 00:05:34.140
hide faulty software.

00:05:34.140 --> 00:05:35.260
There's kind of nowhere to hide.

00:05:35.260 --> 00:05:36.260
Your source code is out there.

00:05:36.260 --> 00:05:39.899
If it doesn't work, you're going to find out really quickly and the community is not going

00:05:39.899 --> 00:05:41.700
to be happy.

00:05:41.700 --> 00:05:47.140
So that's another big benefit is that you can validate your own software.

00:05:47.140 --> 00:05:50.100
It is a higher investment, though.

00:05:50.100 --> 00:05:54.660
So there's a strong community for our developers and our platform administrators.

00:05:54.660 --> 00:06:01.579
So we're doing more and more on RStudio community to support the IT folks who are supporting

00:06:01.579 --> 00:06:05.100
the platform for analysts.

00:06:05.100 --> 00:06:09.260
And last but not least, sometimes you can run into issues with your legal team or your

00:06:09.260 --> 00:06:11.739
info security team.

00:06:11.739 --> 00:06:16.500
And there is commercially licensed R and tools for R available, and sometimes that can help

00:06:16.500 --> 00:06:21.540
assuage some of the legal concerns when you're switching between or when you're moving more

00:06:21.540 --> 00:06:25.420
towards an open source software.

00:06:25.420 --> 00:06:29.940
So okay, now that you've got the open source software, why should we pay for tooling around

00:06:29.940 --> 00:06:33.220
that open source software?

00:06:33.220 --> 00:06:34.220
There's a few different reasons.

00:06:34.220 --> 00:06:40.380
So performance, so I don't know if you've had any experience with the open source tools

00:06:40.380 --> 00:06:45.299
versus the professional tools, but typically you have a little bit better performance definitely

00:06:45.299 --> 00:06:47.779
with the server products that we have.

00:06:47.779 --> 00:06:49.739
You have improved performance.

00:06:49.940 --> 00:06:51.739
It can be deployed in a more secure fashion.

00:06:51.739 --> 00:06:58.540
You can have things like authentication, kind of locking it down, and that helps InfoSec

00:06:58.540 --> 00:07:01.459
feel more confident in the tools.

00:07:01.459 --> 00:07:06.140
And then you can have increased collaboration with your colleagues.

00:07:06.140 --> 00:07:10.779
And then with Connect and other tools, you can do some automations, you can automate

00:07:10.779 --> 00:07:16.940
out some reporting, you can also have a commercial license, which we kind of talked about before,

00:07:16.940 --> 00:07:23.899
but you can have some legal coverage, which makes legal happier.

00:07:23.899 --> 00:07:29.339
You also get maintenance and support, and someone like me and support and solutions

00:07:29.339 --> 00:07:33.459
engineering to give you ideas about how you might want to set up the software and give

00:07:33.459 --> 00:07:35.459
you suggestions.

00:07:35.459 --> 00:07:37.700
So that can be really valuable as well.

00:07:37.700 --> 00:07:41.619
And then there was this idea that Tarif talked about in his keynote yesterday of technology

00:07:41.619 --> 00:07:42.980
philanthropy.

00:07:43.019 --> 00:07:48.739
So by investing as an enterprise in enterprise toolchain for R, we're also helping the broader

00:07:48.739 --> 00:07:54.380
R community and the RStudio community as well.

00:07:54.380 --> 00:07:56.500
So this is another one that I hear a lot, funding.

00:07:56.500 --> 00:07:58.059
There's not enough room in the budget.

00:07:58.059 --> 00:08:00.380
How many people have run into funding barriers?

00:08:00.380 --> 00:08:01.380
Yeah.

00:08:01.380 --> 00:08:02.380
Yeah.

00:08:02.380 --> 00:08:03.540
It's really common.

00:08:03.540 --> 00:08:06.299
This is probably the top one that I hear.

00:08:06.299 --> 00:08:13.980
So my best advice for overcoming the funding issues is just to use the open source toolchain.

00:08:13.980 --> 00:08:20.019
So really deep dive on creating APIs, creating really valuable shiny apps.

00:08:20.019 --> 00:08:22.260
Show them what's possible.

00:08:22.260 --> 00:08:27.040
And then be able to communicate what else is possible with the toolchain.

00:08:27.040 --> 00:08:32.900
So I like folks to start with the open source toolchain and create a demand for a parameterized

00:08:32.900 --> 00:08:34.460
R markdown.

00:08:34.460 --> 00:08:38.059
So really deep dive into the open source toolchain.

00:08:38.059 --> 00:08:44.179
And a lot is actually possible with the open source tools.

00:08:44.179 --> 00:08:46.979
So collaborate with parallel teams through your R community.

00:08:46.979 --> 00:08:50.940
So once you've built up an R community, collaborate with those teams.

00:08:50.940 --> 00:08:55.799
I've seen several teams be successful in collaborating and resource sharing.

00:08:55.799 --> 00:09:01.619
So two different teams and different organizations using one software.

00:09:01.619 --> 00:09:03.979
That's definitely possible.

00:09:04.500 --> 00:09:08.380
Or if there is a team in your organization that's been successful with funding, they

00:09:08.380 --> 00:09:13.580
may know how they may have ideas for you as to how they got that funding made available

00:09:13.580 --> 00:09:17.059
to them.

00:09:17.059 --> 00:09:19.820
And then I kind of covered this in my first point.

00:09:19.820 --> 00:09:25.099
Clearly communicate the possibilities with open source and the possibilities with professional

00:09:25.099 --> 00:09:26.099
software.

00:09:26.099 --> 00:09:29.840
So once you have your proof of concept, there are evaluations of all of our professional

00:09:29.840 --> 00:09:36.719
products that can allow you the opportunity to demonstrate what else is possible.

00:09:36.719 --> 00:09:42.400
And once you create that appetite, I've seen funds become available.

00:09:42.400 --> 00:09:46.640
Oh, the last one.

00:09:46.640 --> 00:09:48.000
Ask good questions.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:55.479
So I think sometimes when we're told no, the automatic response is, oh.

00:09:55.479 --> 00:10:00.919
And it can be hard to kind of pull yourself together and approach that with curiosity.

00:10:00.919 --> 00:10:02.960
Oh, okay.

00:10:02.960 --> 00:10:08.919
Is there any funding changes in the future that you can see coming down the road?

00:10:08.919 --> 00:10:10.400
What about our tool chain for next year?

00:10:10.400 --> 00:10:12.479
Is there going to be any additional funding?

00:10:12.479 --> 00:10:19.840
So sometimes just getting over the, oh, and going to approaching it with curiosity can

00:10:19.840 --> 00:10:23.619
be successful in kind of problem solving.

00:10:23.619 --> 00:10:32.299
And the way I like to think of it is help your manager or whoever told you no solve

00:10:32.299 --> 00:10:33.299
your problem.

00:10:33.299 --> 00:10:35.020
So you want to get them bought in.

00:10:35.020 --> 00:10:42.099
Ask a lot of how, what, open-ended questions in a very curious manner because you're really

00:10:42.099 --> 00:10:45.340
trying to do them a service at this point when you're asking for tooling.

00:10:45.340 --> 00:10:50.979
No one just asks for tools just to have a bigger toolbox.

00:10:50.979 --> 00:10:56.020
The other thing that I hear occasionally is from IT, we can't set up something that

00:10:56.020 --> 00:10:57.020
is free.

00:10:57.020 --> 00:10:59.940
There needs to be a commitment from the business.

00:10:59.940 --> 00:11:06.380
Again, asking good questions becomes really, really important here.

00:11:06.380 --> 00:11:09.659
So what commitment is necessary to use open source tools?

00:11:09.659 --> 00:11:11.179
What does commitment look like?

00:11:11.179 --> 00:11:14.979
Can you give me an idea of what that looks like?

00:11:14.979 --> 00:11:19.039
Is there a separate team that manages open source software?

00:11:19.099 --> 00:11:24.239
So I've had several of my larger accounts that I will work with.

00:11:24.239 --> 00:11:28.400
There's the IT team that they always use, and that team says no, and then they don't

00:11:28.400 --> 00:11:30.080
really know where else to go.

00:11:30.080 --> 00:11:33.880
But sometimes within your organization, there's a research group that's kind of like a mad

00:11:33.880 --> 00:11:39.080
science lab where they're deploying different software, and sometimes those mad scientist

00:11:39.080 --> 00:11:43.679
groups are way more willing to take a chance on open source.

00:11:43.679 --> 00:11:48.960
And another thing to think about is, you know, they're saying no to R, but I can almost

00:11:48.960 --> 00:11:50.640
promise you there's Python somewhere.

00:11:50.640 --> 00:11:53.159
What team is managing Python?

00:11:53.159 --> 00:11:56.840
Like is there a team for managing open source software?

00:11:56.840 --> 00:12:00.719
So sometimes it requires a little out of the box thinking to find the right team.

00:12:00.719 --> 00:12:01.719
All right.

00:12:01.719 --> 00:12:02.719
Let's see.

00:12:02.719 --> 00:12:04.719
Did I get all the points?

00:12:04.719 --> 00:12:05.719
Yes.

00:12:05.719 --> 00:12:06.719
Oh, yeah.

00:12:06.719 --> 00:12:10.780
And asking about the specific policies, because sometimes they'll say, no, that's not in line

00:12:10.780 --> 00:12:11.780
with our policy.

00:12:11.780 --> 00:12:12.780
Well, okay.

00:12:12.880 --> 00:12:13.880
It is.

00:12:13.880 --> 00:12:18.140
So sometimes just, you know, going back and asking a good what question can be really

00:12:18.140 --> 00:12:19.140
helpful.

00:12:19.140 --> 00:12:24.580
There's also a few different options from a technical perspective, so we do have pre-configured

00:12:24.580 --> 00:12:32.299
virtual machines on all of the major cloud platforms, so AWS, Google Cloud, I think Azure

00:12:32.299 --> 00:12:35.219
as of recently.

00:12:35.219 --> 00:12:36.219
Kelly says yes.

00:12:36.219 --> 00:12:37.219
Okay.

00:12:37.219 --> 00:12:38.219
Good.

00:12:38.219 --> 00:12:40.419
Thank you, Kelly.

00:12:40.419 --> 00:12:44.340
And then, yeah, find those open source policy documents.

00:12:44.340 --> 00:12:45.340
Yeah.

00:12:45.340 --> 00:12:46.340
Hit that one twice.

00:12:46.340 --> 00:12:47.340
Really important.

00:12:47.340 --> 00:12:51.460
And then the last thing is explore external partners.

00:12:51.460 --> 00:12:55.320
So if you're really kind of spinning your wheels, you can't find anyone in your IT group

00:12:55.320 --> 00:13:02.219
or your mad scientist IT group that wants to set this up, then we can help you find

00:13:02.219 --> 00:13:07.979
a partner that can come in and set up the server, and sometimes I have several folks

00:13:07.979 --> 00:13:11.619
that will need to do that just to get anything done.

00:13:11.619 --> 00:13:14.640
I'm getting close to time, so I'm going to hurry up.

00:13:14.640 --> 00:13:18.900
So political pressure for other tools and languages.

00:13:18.900 --> 00:13:22.460
So not every tool is right for every problem.

00:13:22.460 --> 00:13:24.340
Don't argue for one tool.

00:13:24.340 --> 00:13:26.179
Instead argue for more tools.

00:13:26.179 --> 00:13:31.900
Again, I like this idea of curiosity, and I've seen it be really successful.

00:13:31.900 --> 00:13:38.419
So asking about the features that they saw in the product, like what is their tangible

00:13:38.419 --> 00:13:40.059
takeaway that they're interested in?

00:13:40.059 --> 00:13:41.859
Are they interested in a dashboard?

00:13:41.859 --> 00:13:43.979
Are they interested in a report?

00:13:43.979 --> 00:13:45.419
What is the takeaway?

00:13:45.419 --> 00:13:48.780
And then in the back of your head, be thinking about could I show them something similar

00:13:48.780 --> 00:13:52.099
with the open source R?

00:13:52.099 --> 00:13:57.739
So just asking those good questions so that you understand what their needs are, and then

00:13:57.739 --> 00:14:02.179
you have your R skills that you can think about how to create that with the tool chain

00:14:02.179 --> 00:14:05.580
that you prefer.

00:14:05.580 --> 00:14:08.700
So how does this align with our goals and needs?

00:14:08.700 --> 00:14:12.059
So asking about how the software, what direction are we going as a team?

00:14:12.059 --> 00:14:16.340
This can be really good for helping you navigate through your career.

00:14:16.340 --> 00:14:18.859
What other tools are available for me?

00:14:18.859 --> 00:14:22.380
So if I run into problems, what are my other options?

00:14:22.380 --> 00:14:27.739
So again, you're kind of recruiting them to help them solve your problem.

00:14:27.739 --> 00:14:34.900
And so just through curiosity and letting them, telling them kind of what's possible.

00:14:34.900 --> 00:14:37.859
And then more tools is not necessarily bad.

00:14:37.859 --> 00:14:42.219
You can definitely have too many tools, but a toolbox with just a bunch of hammers is

00:14:42.219 --> 00:14:44.500
not that helpful.

00:14:44.500 --> 00:14:48.460
In this photo, it would be helpful to have a screwdriver.

00:14:48.460 --> 00:14:50.059
Last but not least, you can do it.

00:14:50.059 --> 00:14:54.820
I've seen a lot of people run into some really stubborn barriers, and I've seen these concepts

00:14:54.820 --> 00:14:55.900
work in action.

00:14:55.900 --> 00:14:56.940
So you can do it.

00:14:56.940 --> 00:15:00.859
You can advocate for your tool chain, and you can be successful using the tools that

00:15:00.859 --> 00:15:02.859
you prefer to use.

00:15:02.859 --> 00:15:05.859
All right.

00:15:05.859 --> 00:15:07.859
Questions?

00:15:07.859 --> 00:15:18.859
Thank you.

00:15:18.859 --> 00:15:23.900
Do you see RStudio Connect as a good way to initially get in the door, I guess, with R

00:15:23.900 --> 00:15:25.900
in an organization?

00:15:25.900 --> 00:15:27.340
Yeah, definitely.

00:15:27.340 --> 00:15:32.940
So I think RStudio Connect is a great way because of the emailing feature.

00:15:32.940 --> 00:15:39.500
So every executive that's consuming your reports is attached to their inbox.

00:15:39.500 --> 00:15:44.020
And so if you can show them the automated reporting where they can get their daily reports

00:15:44.020 --> 00:15:49.539
sent to them at the same time every day, and that can include metadata in the subject title,

00:15:49.539 --> 00:15:52.619
that's a golden way to get buy-in in RStudio Connect.

00:15:52.619 --> 00:15:58.539
You can even do some really nice HTML email formatting so that it looks really great in

00:15:58.539 --> 00:15:59.539
their inbox.

00:15:59.539 --> 00:16:04.979
And I think if more executives were able to see that, they would get more excited about

00:16:04.979 --> 00:16:10.140
the RStudio professional tool chain, specifically Connect.

00:16:10.140 --> 00:16:18.140
I didn't catch it with my face.

00:16:18.140 --> 00:16:27.140
Do you have any experience working with public sector agencies where, I mean, I'm from Washington

00:16:27.140 --> 00:16:33.340
State in the Department of Health, and Microsoft is kind of a religion there.

00:16:33.340 --> 00:16:41.179
And so we have contracts with all these things, and trying to slip this stuff in is more than

00:16:41.179 --> 00:16:42.179
challenging.

00:16:42.179 --> 00:16:43.299
Yeah, definitely.

00:16:43.299 --> 00:16:45.020
So we have several folks.

00:16:45.020 --> 00:16:50.099
So actually, the team that I worked with that had this giant Slack channel, they were actually

